description: The document is the README for Meridian Technologies' API Gateway, detailing its setup, tech stack, and deployment. It uses Python 3.12, FastAPI, SQLAlchemy, Redis, and PostgreSQL. The last modification was on 2024-06-01, and the status is active. It includes environment variables, testing procedures, and deployment via GitHub Actions and ArgoCD.
author: Jordan Lee

description: The document outlines Meridian Technologies' Data Privacy Service for handling GDPR and CCPA requests. It specifies a 30-day SLA for deletions, with current average completion at 4 hours. The service interacts with PostgreSQL, ClickHouse, Redis, S3, and Kafka, with Kafka data expiring naturally. The document is active, last modified on 2024-04-01.
author: Platform Team

description: The document outlines Meridian Technologies' event-processor, a Kafka consumer for event processing, enrichment, and storage. It uses Python 3.11, Kafka, ClickHouse, and GeoIP2, with a 24-hour deduplication window. Known issues include manual GeoIP updates and potential ClickHouse performance limits for high-cardinality events. Status: active.
author: Sarah Chen

description: This document is the README for Meridian Technologies' Feast-based feature store, detailing feature groups, their sources, and update frequencies. It includes user_activity, account_health, and support_metrics feature groups with specific features. The online store uses Redis, and the offline store uses S3/Parquet. The document is active, last modified on 2024-06-01.
author: ML Infra Team

description: This document announces the deprecation of Meridian Technologies' legacy analytics service, which was active until March 2024. It was built on Node.js and MongoDB, with all functionality migrated to an event-processor pipeline. The MongoDB cluster will be decommissioned in December 2024, and no new connections should be made. The document status is outdated.
author: Platform Team

description: This document describes Meridian Technologies' ML Scoring Service, a real-time model serving system using Python 3.10, FastAPI, and MLflow. It supports XGBoost and BERT models for churn prediction and event classification. The service is active as of 2024-07-01, with plans to migrate to Python 3.12 by Q4 2024. Deprecated endpoints include model listing and batch prediction features.
author: Li Wang

description: The notification-service handles outbound notifications via email, Slack, and webhooks using Go 1.21, Kafka, SendGrid, and Slack API. It processes messages from the 'notifications.send' Kafka topic with specific rate limits (100/hour per tenant for email, 1/second for Slack). Failed notifications retry with exponential backoff, moving to a dead letter queue after three failures. The document is current with status 'active'.

The document is a README for Meridian Technologies' workflow-engine, detailing its role in executing customer-defined automation workflows. It specifies limits like 50 workflows per tenant on the Starter plan and 5 actions per workflow. The status is active, with execution guarantees including at-least-once delivery and 30-second timeouts. Limitations include no loops or conditionals, planned for Q1 2025.
author: Product Team

description: ADR-003 outlines Meridian Technologies' phased database migration from a monolithic PostgreSQL to a sharded architecture using Citus. The plan includes three phases, starting in Q1 2024, to shard large tables like 'events' (800GB) by 'tenant_id'. The document notes Citus licensing costs at ~$50K/year and emphasizes forward-only migrations with shadow mode testing. The status is active.
author: Sarah Chen

description: ADR-003 outlines Meridian Technologies' decision to pause the Citus database migration, reverting to Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL for non-events tables. The document states that 40% of engineering time was spent on migration issues, with Aurora costing $30K/year versus Citus's $50K/year. The plan includes moving remaining tables to Aurora, using read replicas, and deferring full sharding to 2025. The document is current with status 'active'.
author: Priya Patel

description: ADR-007 outlines Meridian Technologies' forward-only migration policy to prevent rollback risks. It specifies no 'down' migrations, requiring new forward migrations to fix errors. The document references two incidents, uses Alembic and Flyway tools, and mandates Platform team reviews. Status is active.
author: Sarah Chen

description: This document outlines Meridian Technologies' API rate limiting strategy, effective as of May 2024. It specifies tenant-based rate limits per API Gateway with Redis-backed sliding windows. Default limits include 60/min for Starter, 300/min for Professional, and 1,000/min for Enterprise plans. Exemptions apply to health checks, internal service calls, and webhook endpoints with higher limits. The document is current with active status.
author: Platform Team

description: This document outlines Meridian Technologies' system architecture for their B2B SaaS platform, serving 2,000 tenants with 50M daily events. It details the AWS-based infrastructure, key services like PostgreSQL, Kafka, and ClickHouse, and technical decisions including Citus sharding and 30s event delay. The architecture is current as of July 2024 with active status.
author: Platform Team

description: This document is the ML Platform Guide for Meridian Technologies, last updated in August 2024 by the ML Infrastructure Team. It details three production models, including the Churn Predictor (XGBoost, 45ms P95 latency) and Event Classifier (BERT, 120ms). The guide covers training infrastructure, model serving via FastAPI, and deployment processes. The document is current with active status.
author: ML Infra Team

description: This runbook outlines manual PostgreSQL failover procedures for Meridian Technologies' production environment. It details steps to promote a read replica, update DNS via Route53, and restart application pods. The document was last tested in April 2024 and is currently active. Key elements include specific AWS RDS commands, estimated recovery times of 15-20 minutes, and requirements for DBA-level access and IC approval.
author: Platform Team

description: This document outlines Meridian Technologies' Data Retention Policy, effective August 2024, maintained by Legal and Engineering. It specifies retention periods: 12 months for usage logs, 7 years for payment data, 2 years for Slack messages, and 3 years post-employment for employee data. GDPR and CCPA compliance requirements include 30-day deletion response times. The policy is current with backup procedures and encryption standards.
author: Legal

description: This document outlines Meridian Technologies deployment process, effective June 2024. It details a continuous deployment pipeline with staged rollouts, 30-minute staging soaks, 15-minute canary phases, and automatic rollback if error rates exceed 1%. The policy specifies code freeze (deploy freeze) periods and the emergency deploy exception process for critical fixes during freezes. Requires two approvals including a CODEOWNER.
author: Platform Team

description: Meridian Technologies' Expense Reimbursement Policy, effective January 2024 and active, outlines guidelines for submitting expenses through Expensify within 30 days. It specifies receipt requirements for amounts over $25, manager approval for expenses over $500, and VP approval for over $2,000. The policy covers travel, team events, software subscriptions, and non-reimbursable items, with reimbursements processed within 5 business days. It also details a $100/month wellness benefit for fitness-related expenses.
author: Finance Team

description: This is a draft expense reimbursement policy for Meridian Technologies, proposing changes including a $100/day meal per diem for domestic travel, a three-conference limit per employee, and a $200/month AI/ML tools budget. The document is marked as a draft pending Finance approval, with a proposed effective date of January 1, 2025. Notes suggest potential additions for home office furniture and VP sign-off for AI tools.

The Incident Response Playbook from Meridian Technologies outlines procedures for declaring and managing incidents, effective May 2024. It defines roles like Incident Commander and severity levels (P1-P3), with P1 requiring VP notification and status page updates within 15 minutes. The document specifies post-incident processes, including post-mortems in Notion and action items in Jira. It is current and active, with a blameless post-mortem policy.
author: Platform Team

description: Meridian Technologies' on-call policy outlines responsibilities for backend and infrastructure engineers, requiring participation in weekly on-call rotations from March 1, 2024. Engineers receive $200/day for weekdays and $400/day for weekends/holidays, with specific response time limits (15-30 minutes) and escalation procedures. Post-mortems are required for P1/P2 incidents within 3 business days. The document is current with no noted contradictions.
author: Sarah Chen

description: This is Meridian Technologies' current PTO policy effective September 1, 2024. It outlines annual PTO days (20-25 days) with carryover limits (5-10 days) based on employee levels. The policy includes a minimum 10-day annual usage requirement, blackout periods, and separate sick leave and parental leave provisions. The document is active and supersedes the previous January 2023 policy.
author: HR Team

description: This document outlines Meridian Technologies' 2023 Paid Time Off (PTO) policy, effective January 15, 2023. It specifies PTO allowances by employee level: IC1-IC3 (18 days, 3-day carryover), IC4-IC5 and Managers (22 days, 5-day carryover), and Directors and above (30 days, 10-day carryover). The policy requires 3-business-day advance notice via BambooHR for requests over 3 days and notes a December 20 - January 1 blackout period for the Engineering team. Sick leave provides 8 non-carryover days with doctor's notes for over 5 days. The document is current with no contradictions noted.
author: HR Team

description: This document outlines Meridian Technologies' Remote Work Policy, effective April 2024. It specifies a hybrid-flexible work model with team-specific office days, a $1,500 home office stipend, and $500/year equipment allowance. International remote work is permitted for up to 4 weeks annually with tax responsibilities. The policy is active and includes communication expectations and equipment standards.
author: People Ops

description: Meridian Technologies' internal Information Security Policy, effective February 2024, outlines access control requirements, data classification levels, and security procedures. It mandates Okta SSO with MFA, quarterly access reviews, and 30-day elevated access limits. The document specifies data handling for Public, Internal, Confidential, and Restricted levels, with encryption requirements. Current active policy with 90-day secret rotation and incident reporting protocols.
author: Security Team

description: This document outlines Meridian Technologies' analytics pipeline product specification, authored by David Kim in February 2024. It details data flow with 60-second SLA for event ingestion and 13-25 month data retention based on plans. The pipeline supports track, page view, identify, and group events with query capabilities through dashboards, SQL editors, and APIs. Known limitations include out-of-order event handling and SQL JOIN restrictions.
author: David Kim

description: This document outlines Meridian Technologies' PRD for Dashboard V2, aiming to improve user experience by reducing clicks to 2 or fewer and increasing NPS to 50+. The redesign includes customizable widgets, real-time data, and mobile responsiveness. It is in development with a target Q3 2024 release, and the V1 sunset is scheduled for April 1, 2025.
author: Jessica Liu

description: This is an internal engineering all-hands meeting transcript from August 15, 2024, detailing key updates from Meridian Technologies. The document mentions the completed Aurora migration with 30% improved read query latency, 4 new Q4 engineering hires with referral bonuses up to $10,000, and the upcoming 'Tech Health Score' initiative. The document is current, with no contradictions noted.

This document is a meeting transcript from Meridian Technologies' ML team sync on September 3, 2024. It covers sprint updates, including the deployment of v2.3.1 churn model with AUC improvement to 0.87, issues with anomaly detector retraining due to Feast job delays, and plans to simplify event classification taxonomy. The ml-scoring service needs Python 3.12 upgrade by end of quarter. Document status is current.

This document outlines Meridian Technologies' Q4 2024 product planning meeting. Key initiatives include Dashboard V2 GA on October 1, 2024, with V1 deprecation by April 1, 2025. SQL editor improvements for JOINs with performance warnings and extended timeouts. An AI insights prototype using anomaly detection, with an estimated 2-3 month MVP timeline. The document is a draft, with no contradictions noted.

This document catalog from Meridian Technologies' knowledge base lists 28 documents with metadata including file path, title, author, last modified date, department, and status. It includes 27 active and 1 deprecated document, covering departments like HR, Engineering, Finance, and more. Known data quality issues include missing author and last modified date entries, and some files listed in the manifest are not present on disk. This catalog is useful for locating and managing organizational documents.

This internal document from Meridian Technologies outlines the status of the Aurora migration, scheduled for July 20, with dual-writes and data integrity checks confirmed. It includes a rollback plan involving a 48-hour read-only PG instance and DNS reversal. The document also mentions API endpoint deprecation on September 1, an outdated onboarding document referencing BambooHR instead of Workday, and a tech debt item for meridian-flags documentation. The content is current but highlights several outdated or incomplete resources.

This internal document from Meridian Technologies discusses Kafka data retention policies and the transition from Datadog to Grafana Cloud. It notes Kafka retention is 7 days for most topics, with audit topics at 30 days. The document also mentions a proposed 14-day increase costing $200/month. The migration to Grafana Cloud, effective Q1 2025, includes partial dashboard migration. The content is current, with no contradictions.

Internal incident report from Meridian Technologies detailing two P1 and P2 system failures in Q3 2024. The first incident involved api-gateway 503 errors due to PostgreSQL connection pool exhaustion (45% error rate, 487/500 connections). The second incident involved ml-scoring service serving stale predictions from a mismatched model version (churn-v2.2.0 vs v2.3.1). Both incidents were resolved with root causes identified: reporting service query timeout and hotfix deploy checklist gap. Document status: current.
